<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="jn0a04a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="jn0" href="#jn0a04">JN0: </a>  <a href="../../ff/unbs/jn0all.htm#jn0a04a"> (Cornell) appendix 4(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Her arm is laid for a moment on my knees and then withdrawn and her eyes have revealed her &mdash; secret, vigilant, an enclosed garden &mdash; in a moment. I remember a harmony of red and white that was made for one like her, telling her names and glories, bidding her arise, as for espousal, and come away, bidding her look forth, a spouse, from Amana and from the mountains of the leopards. And I remember that response whereto the perfect tenderness of the body and the soul with all its mystery have gone: Inter ubera mea commorabitur.</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="jn0a04a"><li>A Portrait <a href="../../ulex/ap/ap12d.htm#jn0a04a">ED</a> </li><li><ms href="#jn0a04a">MS NLI IV.254</ms> </li><li>JJA 10:769 </li><li><a name="ap4.1" href="../udra/apda.htm#ap4.1">Usage</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/ap/ap41d.htm#jn0a04a">Draft: ap4.1</a></li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: Cornell 17, pp.41. In Stanislaus Joyce&apos;s hand. This epiphany was used as part of Stephen&apos;s religious meditations in <cite>A Portrait of the Artist as a Young Man</cite> (see <a href="https://archive.org/details/cu31924060276882/page/n183/mode/2up" target="_blank">page 176 of the 1916 B.W. Huebsch edition</a>). The Latin phrase translates as &ldquo;He shall lie between my breasts&rdquo; is from the <cite>Vulgate Old Testament</cite>, Song of Songs, I, xii.</mm> </dd></dl>
